[Our thanks to Thomas for this useful translation. At this time it is
unclear whether there were multiple dogs involved, of which 2 were
caught and their heads recovered for virus confirmation, or just one
dog. Such events can be fairly chaotic on the ground, and so such
uncertainties are not unexpected. So far it would appear that rabies
was confirmed in at least one dog involved in the attacks.
When humans are exposed, immediately washing the wound and
vaccination in the first few days following the bite effectively
prevents the onset of the disease. Of ProMED reports on rabies in
Indonesia (see below), 7/17 involve East Nusa Tenggara, where some 44
people died of the disease in 2005 and probably a similar number in
1998 -- the reports are confused for that time period. In 1998 they
were controlling the disease by killing urban dogs in large numbers,
which at best is totally ineffective. Controlling urban rabies by
annual vaccination of the canine population, especially if the
vaccination campaign is completed in about 4 weeks and timed during
seasonal fertility, so that the maximum number of young dogs can be
vaccinated, has long been shown to work very well, cheaply, and with
maximum cost effectiveness. Frankly, urban rabies control is to
veterinary public health what mastitis control is to farm
veterinarians -- fundamentally simple and straightforward.
For Sikka, go to:
<http://www.fallingrain.com/world/ID/0/Sika.html>http://www.fallingrain.com/world/ID/0/Sika.html>
- Mod.MHJ]
